        <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">EV Ownership Costs vs Petrol</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Beyond the purchase price and finance rate, EVs have significantly lower running costs. Electricity costs approximately $2–$4 per 100km compared to $12–$18 per 100km for petrol. Servicing costs are 30–50% lower because EVs have far fewer moving parts — no oil changes, no timing belts, no exhaust system, and regenerative braking reduces brake wear.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">When you factor in lower running costs, potential FBT savings through a novated lease, green car loan discounts, and state-based incentives (where available), an EV can be cheaper on a total-cost-of-ownership basis than a comparable petrol vehicle despite a higher purchase price.</p>
        <div class="bg-[#0d4d3e]/5 border-l-4 border-[#10b981] rounded-r-lg p-6 my-6"><p class="text-[#0d4d3e] font-lato font-light leading-relaxed">Example: A Tesla Model 3 at $55,000 via novated lease on a $100,000 salary costs approximately $550–$650 per fortnight from pre-tax income, including all running costs. A comparable $45,000 petrol sedan via standard car loan costs approximately $500–$600 per fortnight from after-tax income, plus fuel and servicing on top. The EV can end up costing less despite the higher sticker price.</p></div>
